  "chunk_index": 34,
  "summary": "Colin Lamb confronts Hilary Webber, also known as Rosemary Shirley, regarding her presence at the murder scene at 19 Wilbraham Crescent. After Lamb points out that she lied about returning to the house to retrieve gloves on a warm September day, Hilary admits she went back to steal a clock and shoved it into her bag. She explains that the clock was inscribed with the name \"Rosemary,\" which is her own name, and claims the object had been with her her entire life.\n\nHilary recounts that when she entered the house, she discovered a dead man. While stunned, she placed her clock on a round table by the fireplace, and her hands became covered in blood. She fled the scene to avoid being seen, but she believes someone is framing her. She notes that a postcard sent from Old Bailey Street, containing the words \"remember\" and the number \"4:13,\" suggests someone knows she took the clock. Hilary also speculates about her mysterious parentage, questioning if the dead man was her father and if she was lured to the scene to be made to appear guilty. When Lamb asks for the location of the clock, Hilary reveals she threw it into a neighbor's trash bin.\n\nLater, Colin checks out of the Clarendon Hotel and visits the police station to speak with Hakast. Hakast advises Colin to stay away from the investigation and reveals a letter from a woman describing a specific physical feature of her husband: a scar on the back of his left ear caused by a razor.",
